{"parse":{"title":"Changing Tides","pageid":28794391,"revid":860446055,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:422px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Manuel_Pardal_e_capataz.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Manuel_Pardal_e_capataz.jpg/420px-Manuel_Pardal_e_capataz.jpg\" width=\"420\" height=\"315\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Manuel_Pardal_e_capataz.jpg/630px-Manuel_Pardal_e_capataz.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Manuel_Pardal_e_capataz.jpg/840px-Manuel_Pardal_e_capataz.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"2362\" data-file-height=\"1771\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Manuel_Pardal_e_capataz.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div><b>Manuel Pardal</b> (on right) together with an old friend facing the foreman</div></div></div>\n<p><i><b>Changing Tides</b></i> (Portuguese: <i>Mau Tempo, Mar\u00e9s e Mudan\u00e7a</i> - 1976) is a <a href=\"/wiki/Portuguese_language\" title=\"Portuguese language\">Portuguese</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Feature-length_film\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Feature-length film\">feature-length film</a> by <a href=\"/wiki/Ricardo_Costa_(filmmaker)\" title=\"Ricardo Costa (filmmaker)\">Ricardo Costa</a>, his first <a href=\"/wiki/Docufiction\" title=\"Docufiction\">docufiction</a>, preceding <i><a href=\"/wiki/Bread_and_Wine_(film)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Bread and Wine (film)\">Bread and Wine</a></i> (1981) and <i><a href=\"/wiki/Mists\" title=\"Mists\">Mists</a></i> (2003).\n</p><p>Manuel Pardal, <a href=\"/wiki/Oral_literature\" title=\"Oral literature\">native poet</a> <sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> and fisherman, is the protagonist. This film and a book publication of his poetry, <i>Em Cima do Mar Salgado</i> (On the salted sea),<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> <sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> an anthology of his poems (175 pages), are the single remaining registers of his life and work.\n</p><p>The film was first released by <a href=\"/wiki/R%C3%A1dio_e_Televis%C3%A3o_de_Portugal\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"R\u00e1dio e Televis\u00e3o de Portugal\">RTP</a> (Portuguese national television) in <a href=\"/wiki/1975\" title=\"1975\">1975</a>.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Synopsis\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Synopsis</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Cast\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Cast</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Credits\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Credits</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Bibliographic_references\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Bibliographic references</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">6</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-7\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">7</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Synopsis\">Synopsis</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Changing_Tides&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Synopsis\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Manuel Pardal, a solitary fisherman who makes his meagre living from the sea, a native poet, is a keen observer of human and social conditions. Like some in <a href=\"/wiki/Algarve\" title=\"Algarve\">Algarve</a> (the southern Portuguese coast), or others in <a href=\"/wiki/Alentejo\" title=\"Alentejo\">Alentejo</a>, a flat and dry close region, he is one of the last survivors of the Portuguese <a href=\"/wiki/Oral_literature\" title=\"Oral literature\">oral literature</a>. Illiterate, he follows <a href=\"/wiki/Oral_tradition\" title=\"Oral tradition\">oral tradition</a> common to both regions, consisting in using straight rhyme and free improvisation; the poet is an <a href=\"/wiki/Artist\" title=\"Artist\">artist</a> and an <a href=\"/wiki/Actor\" title=\"Actor\">actor</a>.\n</p><p>In the film, he plays a new role using new instruments, improvising together with a new partner, the filmmaker. He goes fishing offshore the town where he lives, <a href=\"/wiki/Quarteira\" title=\"Quarteira\">Quarteira</a>. Solitude and long waiting make him think. He thinks a lot. He has become a philosopher.\n</p><p>He is now acting. Those waiting for him on the beach, living together with him, his friends, and their children will also play the game, showing themselves together with Pardal making his exciting show (his name means \"Sparrow\" and he exploits it), telling amazing stories, reciting fine verse, asking serious questions.\n</p><p>He also plays <a href=\"/wiki/Portuguese_guitar\" title=\"Portuguese guitar\">Portuguese guitar</a> and sings romantic or \u201cfrank\u201d <a href=\"/wiki/Fado\" title=\"Fado\">fado</a>. <sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Cast\">Cast</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Changing_Tides&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Cast\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li>Manuel Pardal \u2013 fisherman and native poet</li>\n<li>His family</li>\n<li>His friends</li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Credits\">Credits</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Changing_Tides&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Credits\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li>Director and producer: <a href=\"/wiki/Ricardo_Costa_(filmmaker)\" title=\"Ricardo Costa (filmmaker)\">Ricardo Costa</a></li>\n<li>Co-producer:  <a href=\"/wiki/R%C3%A1dio_e_Televis%C3%A3o_de_Portugal\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"R\u00e1dio e Televis\u00e3o de Portugal\">RTP</a></li>\n<li>Photography, camera: Ricardo Costa</li>\n<li>Portuguese guitar: Manuel Pardal</li>\n<li>Spanish guitar: Ab\u00edlio Delca</li>\n<li>Sound: Maur\u00edcio Cunha and Jorge Melo Cardoso</li>\n<li>Editing: Maria Alice Cruz</li>\n<li>Mixing: Jorge Melo Cardoso</li>\n<li>Studios: RTP</li>\n<li>Format: <a href=\"/wiki/16_mm\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"16 mm\">16 mm</a> b/w</li>\n<li>Genre: <a href=\"/wiki/Docufiction\" title=\"Docufiction\">docufiction</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Ethnofiction\" title=\"Ethnofiction\">ethnofiction</a></li>\n<li>Running time: approximately 90 minutes</li>\n<li>Premiere: <a href=\"/wiki/R%C3%A1dio_e_Televis%C3%A3o_de_Portugal\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"R\u00e1dio e Televis\u00e3o de Portugal\">RTP</a>, 1977</li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Bibliographic_references\">Bibliographic references</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Changing_Tides&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Bibliographic references\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><i>O Cais do Olhar</i> by <a href=\"/wiki/Jos%C3%A9_de_Matos-Cruz\" title=\"Jos\u00e9 de Matos-Cruz\">Jos\u00e9 de Matos-Cruz</a>, <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Portuguese_Cinematheque&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Portuguese Cinematheque (page does not exist)\">Portuguese Cinematheque</a>, 1999</li>\n<li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://rcfilmes.com/RCen.pdf\">Ricardo Costa and the flowing pictures</a>, article by Jos\u00e9 de Matos-Cruz</li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Changing_Tides&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/List_of_docufiction_films\" title=\"List of docufiction films\">List of docufiction films</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Changing_Tides&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www3.brandonu.ca/cjns/5.1/grant.pdf\">Manuel Pardal</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofoll